00:13:18.275 --> 00:13:21.533
4Πε
_0 is 9 times 10

00:13:21.533 --> 00:13:22.620
to the 9^(th).
 

00:13:22.620 --> 00:13:27.062
So today we're going to do
something which is a part of a

00:13:27.062 --> 00:13:32.138
great abstraction and it goes as
follows: So I'm gong to take two

00:13:32.138 --> 00:13:36.432
charges,
a q_1 here and

00:13:36.432 --> 00:13:40.878
q_2 here,
and I'm going to give them some

00:13:40.878 --> 00:13:41.408
locations.
 

00:13:41.408 --> 00:13:47.586
So let's say this guy is at
vector r_1,

00:13:47.586 --> 00:13:52.639
this one is at vector
r_2.

00:13:52.639 --> 00:13:55.788
Now, I will really take are of
all the arrows.

00:13:55.788 --> 00:14:00.628
This one is
r_2 -

00:14:00.628 --> 00:14:06.639
r_1,
that arrow there.

00:14:06.639 --> 00:14:09.246
You can check that I didn't
mess up anything,

00:14:09.246 --> 00:14:12.211
because r_1
r_2 -

00:14:12.211 --> 00:14:15.528
r_1 should be
r_2.

00:14:15.528 --> 00:14:19.470
So let's write the coulomb
force now as a vector.

00:14:19.470 --> 00:14:24.811
And you've got to say force on
what, so I'm going to say force

00:14:24.811 --> 00:14:26.298
on 2, due to 1.
 

00:14:26.298 --> 00:14:28.970
Now, you've got to realize it's
a convention.

00:14:28.970 --> 00:14:32.601
So I use a convention:
This is the force on this guy

00:14:32.601 --> 00:14:36.519
and the force due to this guy,
with the second later.

00:14:36.519 --> 00:14:39.379
Now, let's write it out in
detail.

00:14:39.379 --> 00:14:42.388
So that is
q_1 over

00:14:42.388 --> 00:14:45.538
4Πε
_0.

00:14:45.538 --> 00:14:47.710
I'm going to put the
q_2 here.

00:14:47.710 --> 00:14:52.023
Then here I want to write
(r_1 -

00:14:52.023 --> 00:14:54.538
r_2)^(2).
 

00:14:54.538 --> 00:14:57.750
That's the 1 over r^(2),
but then I have to make it a

00:14:57.750 --> 00:14:58.240
vector.
 

00:14:58.240 --> 00:15:00.850
So for the vector part,
once you have the magnitude of

00:15:00.850 --> 00:15:03.741
the vector,
you should multiply by vector

00:15:03.741 --> 00:15:08.070
of length unit 1 going in the
direction of this difference

00:15:08.070 --> 00:15:08.830
vector.
 

00:15:08.830 --> 00:15:11.070
So you can use any symbol you
like.

00:15:11.070 --> 00:15:14.298
One is to say
e_12.

00:15:14.298 --> 00:15:17.990
e's always going to be
unit vector going from 1 to 2,

00:15:17.990 --> 00:15:21.014
or if you're inclined you can
also write

00:15:21.014 --> 00:15:25.126
e_12 as
r_2 -

00:15:25.126 --> 00:15:28.539
r_1 divided by
the length of

00:15:28.539 --> 00:15:32.419
r_2 -
r_1.

00:15:32.419 --> 00:15:34.919
They're all unit vectors.
 

00:15:34.919 --> 00:15:35.720
Now, do you follow that?
 

00:15:35.720 --> 00:15:40.100
I mean, are you having trouble
with unit vectors?

00:15:40.100 --> 00:15:42.850
Anytime I have a vector
pointing from here to there,

00:15:42.850 --> 00:15:45.168
I want to give a magnitude and
direction.

00:15:45.168 --> 00:15:48.457
The magnitude in this case is 1
over the distance squared,

00:15:48.457 --> 00:15:51.861
but you have to append to it a
vector of unit length in that

00:15:51.861 --> 00:15:52.668
direction.
 

00:15:52.668 --> 00:15:55.490
That's what makes it into a
vector.

00:15:55.490 --> 00:16:00.053
For example,
suppose I want to describe that

00:16:00.053 --> 00:16:04.620
vector r,
and it is 7 meters long?

00:16:04.620 --> 00:16:07.379
I cannot write r = 7,
because that doesn't tell you

00:16:07.379 --> 00:16:08.639
which way it's pointing.
 

00:16:08.639 --> 00:16:12.235
So invent the vector called
i, which is a unit vector

00:16:12.235 --> 00:16:15.100
in the x direction and I
multiply it by that.

00:16:15.100 --> 00:16:19.241
So 7i is a vector
parallel to i and 7 times

00:16:19.241 --> 00:16:19.759
long.
 

00:16:19.759 --> 00:16:25.806
7.3i is a vector
parallel to i 7.3 times

00:16:25.806 --> 00:16:27.288
long, okay?
 

00:16:27.288 --> 00:16:30.347
So you need to add a vector of
unit length to the magnitude,

00:16:30.347 --> 00:16:32.370
multiply it to get the actual
vector.

00:16:32.370 --> 00:16:36.110
So that's that formula.
 

00:16:36.110 --> 00:16:38.970
Then if you have many charges,
I'm not going to do that now,

00:16:38.970 --> 00:16:41.168
say one more here,
it'll exert a force on

00:16:41.168 --> 00:16:43.839
q_2,
but you've got to add to the

00:16:43.839 --> 00:16:44.610
force due to 1.
 

00:16:44.610 --> 00:16:45.240
I'm not going to do that.
 

00:16:45.240 --> 00:16:48.500
I'm just taking two guys.
 

00:16:48.500 --> 00:16:56.847
Now, I'm going to formally
write this as equal to the

00:16:56.847 --> 00:17:03.750
electric field at
r_2 times

00:17:03.750 --> 00:17:12.259
q_2,
and this is called a field.

00:17:12.259 --> 00:17:14.220
You see, if you look at this
thing,

00:17:14.220 --> 00:17:17.258
all I've done is rewrite the
expression as something that

00:17:17.258 --> 00:17:19.807
involves a charge of
q�_2 and

00:17:19.807 --> 00:17:23.117
everything else that involves
the q_1 and the

00:17:23.117 --> 00:17:25.125
distance from
q_1 and

00:17:25.125 --> 00:17:26.700
q_2.
 

00:17:26.700 --> 00:17:30.890
So it looks like there's no
real content to giving this

00:17:30.890 --> 00:17:34.048
object a name,
but it's a very profound

00:17:34.048 --> 00:17:38.720
notion, so I've got to tell you
the story that goes with it.

00:17:38.720 --> 00:17:42.308
In Coulomb's Law you say that
q_1 and

00:17:42.308 --> 00:17:45.559
q_2 exert a
force on each other,

00:17:45.559 --> 00:17:46.170
okay?
 

00:17:46.170 --> 00:17:49.136
And the force depends on the
charge and the distance between

00:17:49.136 --> 00:17:49.490
them.
 

00:17:49.490 --> 00:17:53.597
Now I'm going to say
q_1 produces an

00:17:53.597 --> 00:17:58.496
electric field at the location
of q_2 given by

00:17:58.496 --> 00:18:01.674
this vector,
and when I multiply by

00:18:01.674 --> 00:18:05.346
q_2 it gives me
the force on

00:18:05.346 --> 00:18:07.348
q_2.
 

00:18:07.348 --> 00:18:10.890
Now, what's the importance of
the electric field?

00:18:10.890 --> 00:18:14.577
Whereas q_1
and q_2 exist

00:18:14.577 --> 00:18:17.757
only at these two places,
the electric field can be

00:18:17.757 --> 00:18:19.220
defined everywhere.
 

00:18:19.220 --> 00:18:23.207
It doesn't require a second
charge because you see,

00:18:23.207 --> 00:18:26.635
this number you can compute for
any value of

00:18:26.635 --> 00:18:28.630
r_2.
 

00:18:28.630 --> 00:18:33.530
So the picture we have is that
q_1 produces an

00:18:33.530 --> 00:18:37.710
electric field all over space,
and q_2

00:18:37.710 --> 00:18:41.308
experiences that field and gets
repelled as a result,

00:18:41.308 --> 00:18:46.766
and the force it feels is the
field at that point times

00:18:46.766 --> 00:18:49.088
q_2.
 

00:18:49.088 --> 00:18:54.798
In general, we say there's an
electric field at this point in

00:18:54.798 --> 00:18:55.558
space.
 

00:18:55.558 --> 00:19:00.576
If you put a charge q
there it should experience a

00:19:00.576 --> 00:19:04.338
force q times the
electric field.

00:19:04.338 --> 00:19:06.800
So to understand this,
the charges are only in two

00:19:06.800 --> 00:19:08.911
places in our example,
but the field due to

00:19:08.911 --> 00:19:10.868
q_1 is
everywhere.

00:19:10.868 --> 00:19:14.542
At every point in space I can
compute a field due to

00:19:14.542 --> 00:19:16.200
q_1.
 

00:19:16.200 --> 00:19:18.241
So the field,
you can see,

00:19:18.241 --> 00:19:23.144
will turn into a force if you
multiply it by a charge you put

00:19:23.144 --> 00:19:25.838
at the location of the field.
 

00:19:25.838 --> 00:19:28.452
So if you've got one charge
here, I claim there's a field

00:19:28.452 --> 00:19:31.558
here, there's field there;
there's a field everywhere due

00:19:31.558 --> 00:19:32.338
to this guy.
 

00:19:32.338 --> 00:19:35.112
How do I know,
because if you put a test

00:19:35.112 --> 00:19:37.598
charge it begins to feel a
force.

00:19:37.598 --> 00:19:41.493
So one way to say it,
is that the field is the force

00:19:41.493 --> 00:19:44.930
on a unit charge you put at that
location,

00:19:44.930 --> 00:19:48.345
unit charge because if
q_2 is equal to

00:19:48.345 --> 00:19:52.140
1 then numerically E is
exactly equal to the force.

00:19:52.140 --> 00:19:54.845
If I go to you and say,
"Find out the electric

00:19:54.845 --> 00:19:56.358
field at this point."
 

00:19:56.358 --> 00:19:57.039
You say, "Okay,
where?"

00:19:57.039 --> 00:19:58.519
I say, "Here."
 

00:19:58.519 --> 00:20:02.769
What do you think you have to
do to measure the field?

00:20:02.769 --> 00:20:04.200
Yes?
 

00:20:04.200 --> 00:20:07.117
Student:  Add up all the
forces on that field from the

00:20:07.117 --> 00:20:09.452
different charges,
or add up all of the fields at

00:20:09.452 --> 00:20:10.279
that point...
 

00:20:10.279 --> 00:20:10.680
Prof: No, okay.
 

00:20:10.680 --> 00:20:13.063
Her answer was,
"If I want the field here,

00:20:13.063 --> 00:20:15.601
I should find out where all the
charges are,"

00:20:15.601 --> 00:20:16.118
right?
 

00:20:16.118 --> 00:20:18.746
"Find all the forces they
will exert on this guy,

00:20:18.746 --> 00:20:20.680
on the unit charge here,"
right?

00:20:20.680 --> 00:20:22.778
But I'm telling you,
that's correct.

00:20:22.778 --> 00:20:25.439
That's the theoretical way to
calculate the field at that

00:20:25.439 --> 00:20:28.144
point, but suppose you're an
experimentalist and you don't

00:20:28.144 --> 00:20:29.759
want to know what produced it.
 

00:20:29.759 --> 00:20:33.309
You just want an answer to
what's the field here.

00:20:33.309 --> 00:20:34.940
What will you do?
 

00:20:34.940 --> 00:20:35.519
Yes?
 

00:20:35.519 --> 00:20:36.799
Student:  Place a test
charge.

00:20:36.799 --> 00:20:37.950
Prof: Okay, and then?
 

00:20:37.950 --> 00:20:41.009
Student:  And then see
what happens to it.

00:20:41.009 --> 00:20:44.221
Prof: By `see what
happens', you've got to be

00:20:44.221 --> 00:20:46.865
more--so his answer was:
put a test charge,

00:20:46.865 --> 00:20:48.440
and see what happens.
 

00:20:48.440 --> 00:20:50.160
Now, you've got to be more
precise.

00:20:50.160 --> 00:20:53.854
I think you know what you
meant, but I want you to finish

00:20:53.854 --> 00:20:54.910
that sentence.
 

00:20:54.910 --> 00:20:55.666
Student:  Okay.
 

00:20:55.666 --> 00:20:57.836
Well, you can measure the force
by measuring the acceleration on

00:20:57.836 --> 00:20:58.319
the charge.
 

00:20:58.319 --> 00:20:58.859
Prof: Very good.
 

00:20:58.859 --> 00:20:59.490
See, that's what I want.
 

00:20:59.490 --> 00:21:01.640
When you said,
"See what happens,"

00:21:01.640 --> 00:21:02.740
does it get married?
 

00:21:02.740 --> 00:21:03.897
Does it have children?
 

00:21:03.897 --> 00:21:05.528
That's not what I meant,
okay?

00:21:05.528 --> 00:21:07.210
But you did give the right
answer.

00:21:07.210 --> 00:21:10.042
The answer was,
by `see what happens',

00:21:10.042 --> 00:21:14.178
you put the charge there,
and you see what acceleration

00:21:14.178 --> 00:21:15.480
it undergoes.
 

00:21:15.480 --> 00:21:19.625
Then that acceleration is
the--that times the mass is the

00:21:19.625 --> 00:21:21.548
force it's experiencing.
 

00:21:21.548 --> 00:21:25.038
That should be q that
you place there times E.

00:21:25.038 --> 00:21:27.480
If q was 1 that force
itself is equal to E.

00:21:27.480 --> 00:21:33.394
If q was 10 you've got
to divide the force by 10 to get

00:21:33.394 --> 00:21:35.140
the field there.
 

00:21:35.140 --> 00:21:40.730
So, the field is like the sound
of one hand clapping.

00:21:40.730 --> 00:21:43.720
People say one hand clapping is
Zen concept, but the field is

00:21:43.720 --> 00:21:46.411
like that, because you don't
need two charges to have a

00:21:46.411 --> 00:21:46.910
field.
 

00:21:46.910 --> 00:21:49.029
You just need one charge.
 

00:21:49.029 --> 00:21:50.880
So here is how we understand
that.

00:21:50.880 --> 00:21:54.578
You put a charge q.
 

00:21:54.578 --> 00:21:58.308
If you go here something has
happened there,

00:21:58.308 --> 00:21:58.828
see?
 

00:21:58.828 --> 00:22:00.790
You don't need to put a second
charge there to conclude

00:22:00.790 --> 00:22:01.700
something has happened.
 

00:22:01.700 --> 00:22:06.160
Something really is different
at this location because the

00:22:06.160 --> 00:22:08.430
charge q is present.
 

00:22:08.430 --> 00:22:09.598
What is different?
 

00:22:09.598 --> 00:22:13.292
What is different is that when
this guy was not here and I put

00:22:13.292 --> 00:22:15.108
a charge, it just sat there.
 

00:22:15.108 --> 00:22:19.560
Whereas when this guy is here
and I put a charge,

00:22:19.560 --> 00:22:21.880
it experiences a force.
 

00:22:21.880 --> 00:22:25.711
So if you put a 1 coulomb here
it experiences a force which is

00:22:25.711 --> 00:22:29.711
1 times the field at that point,
therefore, this charge has

00:22:29.711 --> 00:22:35.920
distorted the space around it,
in fact, everywhere.

00:22:35.920 --> 00:22:39.910
Now, if you've got many,
many, many charges,

00:22:39.910 --> 00:22:43.018
then they will all try to
produce a force on a unit charge

00:22:43.018 --> 00:22:44.856
and you should,
like you said,

00:22:44.856 --> 00:22:47.916
add up the vectors,
which are the forces due to all

00:22:47.916 --> 00:22:50.548
the other charges on that one
location,

00:22:50.548 --> 00:22:54.308
on a test charge on that
location.

00:22:54.308 --> 00:23:01.010
So the field is the sum of the
field due to all the charges at

00:23:01.010 --> 00:23:02.440
that point.
 

00:23:02.440 --> 00:23:10.309
Now, Coulomb's Law doesn't work
when charges are moving.

00:23:10.309 --> 00:23:11.108
Why is that?
 

00:23:11.108 --> 00:23:15.769
Have you any idea why you
cannot use it?

00:23:15.769 --> 00:23:16.450
Yes?
 

00:23:16.450 --> 00:23:17.390
Student:  The radius is
changing?

00:23:17.390 --> 00:23:17.880
Prof: Pardon me?
 

00:23:17.880 --> 00:23:19.608
Student:  r is
changing?

00:23:19.608 --> 00:23:22.875
Prof: r is
changing so we'll keep changing

00:23:22.875 --> 00:23:25.797
it as the charge moves,
but it's only an approximation

00:23:25.797 --> 00:23:26.670
when charges move.
 

00:23:26.670 --> 00:23:30.299
Do you know why?
 

00:23:30.299 --> 00:23:31.528
Yep?
 

00:23:31.528 --> 00:23:34.578
Student:  There's a
magnetic field?

00:23:34.578 --> 00:23:36.016
Prof: True,
but even the electric

00:23:36.016 --> 00:23:37.490
field--his answer was magnetic
field,

00:23:37.490 --> 00:23:40.259
but even the electric field is
not properly given.

00:23:40.259 --> 00:23:41.308
Yes?
 

00:23:41.308 --> 00:23:44.790
Student:  Is the
electric field affected by

00:23:44.790 --> 00:23:47.348
something like the Doppler
Effect?

00:23:47.348 --> 00:23:50.440
Prof: Not the Doppler,
something else.

00:23:50.440 --> 00:23:53.420
If Coulomb's Law were exact,
okay?

00:23:53.420 --> 00:23:55.108
Here is what I can do.
 

00:23:55.108 --> 00:23:59.539
You take a coulomb and you sit
at the other end of the galaxy.

00:23:59.539 --> 00:24:01.538
I have a coulomb here.
 

00:24:01.538 --> 00:24:03.847
You know the force my coulomb
exerts on yours because it's

00:24:03.847 --> 00:24:04.740
pushing against you.
 

00:24:04.740 --> 00:24:05.630
You hold it.
 

00:24:05.630 --> 00:24:08.470
Now suddenly I move my coulomb
away from you by a tiny amount.

00:24:08.470 --> 00:24:10.740
What will you feel?
 

00:24:10.740 --> 00:24:12.910
You will feel the force is
reduced.

00:24:12.910 --> 00:24:14.108
Yes?
 

00:24:14.108 --> 00:24:15.309
Student:  Relativity
is...

00:24:15.309 --> 00:24:18.015
Prof: Yes,
so the special theory does not

00:24:18.015 --> 00:24:20.787
allow that,
because I have managed to

00:24:20.787 --> 00:24:24.008
communicate with you,
arbitrarily far,

00:24:24.008 --> 00:24:25.410
instantaneously.
 

00:24:25.410 --> 00:24:27.808
The minute I move this charge,
you know about it,

00:24:27.808 --> 00:24:29.460
because your charge moved away.
 

00:24:29.460 --> 00:24:31.866
For example,
if your charge was connected to

00:24:31.866 --> 00:24:33.670
a spring,
and it had been extended to

00:24:33.670 --> 00:24:35.220
some amount because of this
charge,

00:24:35.220 --> 00:24:38.318
the minute I move it your
spring will move.

00:24:38.318 --> 00:24:42.477
That instantaneous
communication is forbidden by

00:24:42.477 --> 00:24:46.368
the special theory,
so it does not happen.

00:24:46.368 --> 00:24:50.163
So the correct way to do it,
it'll maybe come later in the

00:24:50.163 --> 00:24:52.644
course,
so probably not even at the end

00:24:52.644 --> 00:24:55.830
of this course,
but the proper way to do that

00:24:55.830 --> 00:25:00.440
is to in the end realize that
the electric field at this point

00:25:00.440 --> 00:25:04.519
is not only due to what the
charges are doing now,

00:25:04.519 --> 00:25:07.210
but what they were doing in the
past.

00:25:07.210 --> 00:25:10.430
Because if some charge at the
other end of the galaxy did

00:25:10.430 --> 00:25:13.538
something it takes some time,
namely traveling at the speed

00:25:13.538 --> 00:25:16.853
of light,
to carry that information from

00:25:16.853 --> 00:25:18.269
there to here.
 

00:25:18.269 --> 00:25:21.435
So it's the delayed response to
all the motion in the charges

00:25:21.435 --> 00:25:23.970
that you've got to add to find
the field here.

00:25:23.970 --> 00:25:26.394
That's what makes the
computation of the electric

00:25:26.394 --> 00:25:27.910
field much more complicated.
 

00:25:27.910 --> 00:25:31.509
But if you promise me charges
never move then the location now

00:25:31.509 --> 00:25:34.999
is the location last year,
the location a million years

00:25:34.999 --> 00:25:37.348
ago, then you can use Coulomb's
Law.

00:25:37.348 --> 00:25:39.473
Coulomb's Law is good for
electrostatics,

00:25:39.473 --> 00:25:42.660
but in real life charges are
moving, so you cannot really use

00:25:42.660 --> 00:25:43.509
the formula.
 

00:25:43.509 --> 00:25:45.612
Now, in our room,
if you put a charge here and

00:25:45.612 --> 00:25:47.386
another charge there,
if you move this,

00:25:47.386 --> 00:25:49.769
that guy will move pretty much
instantaneously.

00:25:49.769 --> 00:25:52.567
That's because the time it
takes a light signal to go from

00:25:52.567 --> 00:25:54.776
here to there is so small,
you may treat it as

00:25:54.776 --> 00:25:55.660
instantaneous.
 

00:25:55.660 --> 00:25:58.108
So Coulomb's Law is used in
electrical circuits and so on.

00:25:58.108 --> 00:26:01.330
You don't worry about the time
of transit because it's too

00:26:01.330 --> 00:26:03.449
small,
but over longer distances,

00:26:03.449 --> 00:26:06.544
where the time it takes for
light to travel becomes

00:26:06.544 --> 00:26:09.750
non-negligible,
you cannot use Coulomb's Law.

00:26:09.750 --> 00:26:10.670
It's not wrong.
 

00:26:10.670 --> 00:26:14.259
It is not appropriate when
charges are moving.

00:26:14.259 --> 00:26:20.237
However, it will always be true
that if you go to any one point

00:26:20.237 --> 00:26:26.310
the force on any charge q
you put there is q times

00:26:26.310 --> 00:26:31.078
electric field at that point,
okay?

00:26:31.078 --> 00:26:33.938
So the electric field notion
survives because it doesn't

00:26:33.938 --> 00:26:35.029
violate relativity.
 

00:26:35.029 --> 00:26:38.433
It says if the field here is so
much q will experience

00:26:38.433 --> 00:26:41.497
the force q times
E, but the complication

00:26:41.497 --> 00:26:43.200
is what is the field here?
 

00:26:43.200 --> 00:26:46.707
Well, it's due to everybody
else, and it's not only due to

00:26:46.707 --> 00:26:49.569
everybody else right now,
but everybody else from the

00:26:49.569 --> 00:26:52.063
dawn of time because things have
been moving and shaking and

00:26:52.063 --> 00:26:53.118
sending signals to us.
 

00:26:53.118 --> 00:26:56.750
We collect all that and see
what lands here at this instant.

00:26:56.750 --> 00:26:58.920
That decides the field here.
 

00:26:58.920 --> 00:27:01.750
So that's the computation of
the field, but the response to

00:27:01.750 --> 00:27:02.970
the field is very easy.
 

00:27:02.970 --> 00:27:06.873
You put a test charge;
q times E is the

00:27:06.873 --> 00:27:07.650
answer.
 

00:27:07.650 --> 00:27:10.946
So in modern physics,
in theories that are compatible

00:27:10.946 --> 00:27:14.434
with the special theory of
relativity we break the force

00:27:14.434 --> 00:27:15.640
into two parts.
 

00:27:15.640 --> 00:27:19.390
Charges don't immediately
interact with other charges.

00:27:19.390 --> 00:27:22.346
Charges produce a field,
and the field may even

00:27:22.346 --> 00:27:26.460
propagate outwards at the speed
of light if you make motions,

00:27:26.460 --> 00:27:29.339
but another charge at the
location of that particular

00:27:29.339 --> 00:27:32.000
point will respond to the field
at that point.

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:34.098
So it's not responding to the
charge right now.

00:27:34.098 --> 00:27:38.025
It's responding to the field
this charge produced at its

00:27:38.025 --> 00:27:38.808
location.
 

00:27:38.808 --> 00:27:41.577
So all of electromagnetic
theory is going to contain two

00:27:41.577 --> 00:27:41.980
parts.
 

00:27:41.980 --> 00:27:44.243
The first part is,
find the field due to this

00:27:44.243 --> 00:27:46.761
charge configuration,
that charge configuration,

00:27:46.761 --> 00:27:49.641
maybe due to various currents,
and the second part is,

00:27:49.641 --> 00:27:53.338
given the field,
find the response of charges to

00:27:53.338 --> 00:27:54.288
the field.
 

00:27:54.288 --> 00:27:57.038
So you understand charges play
a double role.

00:27:57.038 --> 00:28:00.848
They are the producers of the
field.

00:28:00.848 --> 00:28:03.828
They are also the ones who
respond to the field.

00:28:03.828 --> 00:28:06.019
If you don't have a charge you
cannot produce field.

00:28:06.019 --> 00:28:08.078
If you don't have a charge you
cannot experience it,

00:28:08.078 --> 00:28:09.210
you cannot play that game.
 

00:28:09.210 --> 00:28:12.449
To gain membership into
electrostatic interactions

00:28:12.449 --> 00:28:14.298
you've got to have charge.
 

00:28:14.298 --> 00:28:17.190
So neutrons cannot do that,
but they can do other things.

00:28:17.190 --> 00:28:20.556
Like I said,
they take part in nuclear

00:28:20.556 --> 00:28:24.650
force, in fact,
just as well as protons do.

00:28:24.650 --> 00:28:29.289
All right, so let's go back now
to the simplest problem in the

00:28:29.289 --> 00:28:32.789
world: the electric field due to
one charge.

00:28:32.789 --> 00:28:34.470
The formula is very simple.
 

00:28:34.470 --> 00:28:36.710
Let's put that charge at the
origin.

00:28:36.710 --> 00:28:40.064
And the electric field due to 1
charge is q over

00:28:40.064 --> 00:28:42.858
4Πε
_0,

00:28:42.858 --> 00:28:47.160
1 over r^(2) if you're
here,

00:28:47.160 --> 00:28:48.880
and that's your r vector.
 

00:28:48.880 --> 00:28:52.460
The field at this point is that
magnitude,

00:28:52.460 --> 00:28:55.211
and I'm going to write
e_r_

00:28:55.211 --> 00:28:58.960
meaning a vector of unit
length in the radial direction.

00:28:58.960 --> 00:29:02.490
Once again, I will tell you if
you want, you can write that as

00:29:02.490 --> 00:29:05.732
the position vector divided by
the length of the position

00:29:05.732 --> 00:29:06.369
vector.
 

00:29:06.369 --> 00:29:09.088
They're equivalent ways.
 

00:29:09.088 --> 00:29:11.443
If I write it the second way,
you've got to be a little

00:29:11.443 --> 00:29:11.880
careful.
 

00:29:11.880 --> 00:29:15.863
It'll look like qr over
4Πε

00:29:15.863 --> 00:29:18.150
_0r^(3).
 

00:29:18.150 --> 00:29:21.557
Don't get fooled into thinking
the field is falling at 1 over

00:29:21.557 --> 00:29:22.410
r^(3).
 

00:29:22.410 --> 00:29:25.819
It's really 1 over
r^(2)^( )because there's

00:29:25.819 --> 00:29:27.558
an r on the top.
 

00:29:27.558 --> 00:29:30.108
See, if you write it as 1 over
r^(2) put unit vector.

00:29:30.108 --> 00:29:32.681
If you write it as 1 over
r^(3 )put the position

00:29:32.681 --> 00:29:33.108
vector.
 

00:29:33.108 --> 00:29:36.349
They're all saying the same
thing.

00:29:36.349 --> 00:29:39.048
So here you have this formula.
 

00:29:39.048 --> 00:29:41.675
If you're a person who likes to
work with formulas this is all

00:29:41.675 --> 00:29:42.150
you need.
 

00:29:42.150 --> 00:29:45.700
You manipulate the stuff on
paper, and you add different

00:29:45.700 --> 00:29:48.539
fields, but people like to
visualize this.

00:29:48.539 --> 00:29:50.450
So how do I visualize this?
 

00:29:50.450 --> 00:29:52.200
That's the real question.
 

00:29:52.200 --> 00:29:56.880
So here's a very popular method
for visualizing this formula.

00:29:56.880 --> 00:30:00.480
You know, you've got,
for example--suppose someone

00:30:00.480 --> 00:30:04.743
