potential at
x_2 is the

01:07:21.137 --> 01:07:24.168
integral of the force from
x_1 to

01:07:24.168 --> 01:07:25.840
x_2.
 

01:07:25.840 --> 01:07:29.409
This is how potential is
defined.

01:07:29.409 --> 01:07:32.599
This is the reason why,
if you knew the potential minus

01:07:32.599 --> 01:07:36.869
the derivative gives the force,
and if you knew the force,

01:07:36.869 --> 01:07:41.389
its integral will give you the
change in potential.

01:07:41.389 --> 01:07:44.909
All right, so now when you do
rotations,

01:07:44.909 --> 01:07:48.920
whatever you had for force you
had for torque,

01:07:48.920 --> 01:07:53.659
and whatever played the role of
x is played by

01:07:53.659 --> 01:07:55.210
θ.
 

01:07:55.210 --> 01:07:57.797
In other words,
in rotational dynamics torque

01:07:57.797 --> 01:08:00.739
is to force--just like one of
the SAT questions.

01:08:00.739 --> 01:08:04.344
Torque is to force as
θ is to x,

01:08:04.344 --> 01:08:06.039
and work is just work.
 

01:08:06.039 --> 01:08:10.949
If you want to calculate the
work done by the dipole,

01:08:10.949 --> 01:08:15.744
but if you like the potential
energy when it's at an angle

01:08:15.744 --> 01:08:20.962
θ and its potential
energy when it's at angle 0 is

01:08:20.962 --> 01:08:25.252
the integral of the torque
dθ from 0 to

01:08:25.252 --> 01:08:27.020
θ.
 

01:08:27.020 --> 01:08:29.460
Now, what is the torque?
 

01:08:29.460 --> 01:08:34.291
The torque is
-pEsinθ

01:08:34.291 --> 01:08:40.328
dθ from 0 to
θ.

01:08:40.328 --> 01:08:44.176
There's a minus sign because if
θ tries to

01:08:44.176 --> 01:08:47.310
increase, the torque tries to
decrease it.

01:08:47.310 --> 01:08:50.930
That's why it has got a minus
sign.

01:08:50.930 --> 01:08:53.182
Now, integral of minus
sinθ is

01:08:53.182 --> 01:08:55.648
cosθ,
so you will get

01:08:55.648 --> 01:09:00.201
pEcosθ -
pEcos 0 which is

01:09:00.201 --> 01:09:03.643
-pE,
and that is supposed to equal

01:09:03.643 --> 01:09:07.270
to U(θ) -
U(0).

01:09:07.270 --> 01:09:12.841
By comparing the two
expressions you can identify

01:09:12.841 --> 01:09:17.899
U(θ) to be--
sorry, this is

01:09:17.899 --> 01:09:22.020
U(0) minus
U(θ),

01:09:22.020 --> 01:09:25.567
therefore
U(θ) is

01:09:25.567 --> 01:09:29.510
equal to
-pEcosθ,

01:09:29.510 --> 01:09:37.430
or just -p dot E.
 

01:09:37.430 --> 01:09:43.194
So that's the final formula you
have to remember,

01:09:43.194 --> 01:09:47.760
that the--can we bring it down
here?

01:09:47.760 --> 01:09:51.210
When you have a dipole in an
electric field,

01:09:51.210 --> 01:09:54.925
it has a potential energy
associated with the angle which

01:09:54.925 --> 01:10:00.002
is -p dot E,
and if you draw a picture of

01:10:00.002 --> 01:10:05.408
that as a function of
θ it goes like

01:10:05.408 --> 01:10:06.310
this.
 

01:10:06.310 --> 01:10:10.078
θ = 0 is when the
dipole is parallel to the field.

01:10:10.078 --> 01:10:15.159
That's when it has the minimum
energy, -pE.

01:10:15.159 --> 01:10:17.869
At 90 degrees, energy is 0.
 

01:10:17.869 --> 01:10:22.010
At 180 degrees, it's maximum.
 

01:10:22.010 --> 01:10:25.789
And the torque is just
-dU/dθ and

01:10:25.789 --> 01:10:29.788
you can see that the torque here
and there are zero,

01:10:29.788 --> 01:10:32.100
but this is the point of stable
equilibrium.

01:10:32.100 --> 01:10:34.680
That's the point of unstable
equilibrium.

01:10:34.680 --> 01:10:37.877
See, if this was a potential
energy like a shape of the

01:10:37.877 --> 01:10:40.006
ground,
if you left a marble there

01:10:40.006 --> 01:10:42.585
it'll stay there,
but if it moved a little bit,

01:10:42.585 --> 01:10:43.840
it would roll down hill.
 

01:10:43.840 --> 01:10:46.626
But if you left the marble here
it'll stay there,

01:10:46.626 --> 01:10:49.529
but if you move it,
it'll rattle back and forth.

01:10:49.529 --> 01:10:51.000
That's a stable equilibrium.
 

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:52.100
That's unstable.
 

01:10:52.100 --> 01:10:55.760
So for the dipole when it's
parallel to the field you are

01:10:55.760 --> 01:10:59.420
here, and at anti-parallel to
the field you are there.

01:10:59.420 --> 01:11:02.328
The difference is when you're
parallel and you move it a

01:11:02.328 --> 01:11:05.354
little bit,
it'll have stable oscillations,

01:11:05.354 --> 01:11:09.779
whereas if at anti-parallel if
you move it a little bit it'll

01:11:09.779 --> 01:11:12.948
flip over completely and come
down here.

01:11:12.948 --> 01:11:18.381
All right, so I'm going to
summarize the main points so you

01:11:18.381 --> 01:11:21.380
can carry that with you,
okay?

01:11:21.380 --> 01:11:24.756
We saw today that we should
think in terms of electric field

01:11:24.756 --> 01:11:28.074
from now on, and we no longer
talk about direct interaction

01:11:28.074 --> 01:11:29.220
between charges.
 

01:11:29.220 --> 01:11:33.661
We say charges produce fields,
and fields act on charges to

01:11:33.661 --> 01:11:34.578
move them.
 

01:11:34.578 --> 01:11:37.462
The force of a field on a
charge is just q times

01:11:37.462 --> 01:11:38.050
E.
 

01:11:38.050 --> 01:11:41.485
The field is found by adding
the field due to all the charges

01:11:41.485 --> 01:11:44.063
in the universe,
provided they're all at rest,

01:11:44.063 --> 01:11:46.238
and you just add by Coulomb's
Law.

01:11:46.238 --> 01:11:49.685
So we found the field due to a
dipole allowing the axis and

01:11:49.685 --> 01:11:51.350
perpendicular to the axis.
 

01:11:51.350 --> 01:11:54.162
We saw the notion of field
lines as a good way to visualize

01:11:54.162 --> 01:11:56.538
what's going on in the vicinity
of the charges.

01:11:56.538 --> 01:11:59.470
The lines tell you the
direction where the field is,

01:11:59.470 --> 01:12:01.439
and they tell you in your line
density,

01:12:01.439 --> 01:12:04.109
lines cutting a unit area
perpendicular to them,

01:12:04.109 --> 01:12:05.868
the strength of the field.
 

01:12:05.868 --> 01:12:09.746
Then I calculated for you the
field of a dipole along the axis

01:12:09.746 --> 01:12:11.779
and perpendicular to the axis.
 

01:12:11.779 --> 01:12:14.314
There are a lot of formulas,
but one thing you should carry

01:12:14.314 --> 01:12:14.970
in your head.
 

01:12:14.970 --> 01:12:18.849
When you've got two equal and
opposite charges and you go very

01:12:18.849 --> 01:12:22.029
far, the field will go like 1
over r^(3).

01:12:22.029 --> 01:12:25.537
The 1 over r^(2) part of
them is canceled,

01:12:25.537 --> 01:12:26.050
okay?
 

01:12:26.050 --> 01:12:28.345
That's the main point,
and it goes like 1 over

01:12:28.345 --> 01:12:31.253
r^(3) times 2 in one
place, and 1 over r^(3)

01:12:31.253 --> 01:12:32.529
times 1 in one place.
 

01:12:32.529 --> 01:12:33.488
It doesn't matter.
 

01:12:33.488 --> 01:12:35.939
The main thing is it's 1 over
r^(3).

01:12:35.939 --> 01:12:39.359
Finally, if you take a dipole
and you put it in an electric

01:12:39.359 --> 01:12:41.409
field,
it tends to line up because

01:12:41.409 --> 01:12:43.506
there's a torque,
p cross E,

01:12:43.506 --> 01:12:44.448
trying to line it up.
 

01:12:44.448 --> 01:12:48.059
With that torque you can
associate a potential energy by

01:12:48.059 --> 01:12:51.798
the usual formula that the
torque is minus a derivative of

01:12:51.798 --> 01:12:53.439
the potential energy.
 

01:12:53.439 --> 01:12:56.310
That potential energy is
-p dot E.

01:12:56.310 --> 01:12:59.310
Some of these things may come
in handy later on.

01:12:59.310 --> 01:13:02.243
So you don't have to memorize
them, but they'll be involved

01:13:02.243 --> 01:13:02.800
later on.
 

01:13:02.800 --> 01:13:08.000
 
 

